# AuRA — Automated Repair Assistant
## End-to-End Proof of Concept (POC) Plan

*Job-level repair-job review for fleet maintenance, built on AWS using AI agents, semantic search, an ontology, and (later) a knowledge graph.*

---

## 1. Point of view (POV) — why this, and why now

Today, Maintenance Supervisors (MS) review repair jobs by hand — checking whether the parts used, labour hours, and cost are reasonable, and whether anything looks like an error or fraud. With roughly **13 million jobs per year**, reviewing every job manually is impossible, so supervisors spot-check a small fraction. The consequence is simple: most errors and anomalies are never seen.

The bet behind AuRA is that the *first pass* of this review can be automated. AuRA reads each job record, compares it against what is normal for that repair type on that vehicle type, and produces a structured report with a quality score and specific findings. The supervisor stops searching for problems and instead reviews a short, ranked list of jobs that AuRA has flagged, with the reasons attached.

The strategic value is threefold. **Coverage** goes from a few percent of jobs to effectively all of them. **Consistency** improves, because every job is judged against the same baseline rather than each supervisor's memory. And **supervisor time** shifts from hunting to deciding — they spend their hours on the jobs that actually warrant it.

This document covers the job-level pilot only. RO-level and fleet-level review are deliberately out of scope for the POC and are addressed in the roadmap at the end.

---

## 2. Scope of the POC

**In scope**
- Job-level validation of individual repair job records.
- Numeric reasonableness checks (parts, labour hours, cost vs. norms for repair-type × vehicle-type).
- Free-text understanding of the work description.
- A structured validation report per job: quality score, list of findings, and supporting evidence.
- A reviewer interface (or report feed) for a small number of supervisors at selected locations.

**Out of scope (deferred to later phases)**
- RO-level review (patterns across all jobs on one Repair Order, e.g. job stacking).
- Fleet-level trend analysis (across units, locations, technicians over time).
- A full production knowledge graph (the data is *modelled* to be graph-ready, but graph traversal is not the pilot's job).
- Automated actions — AuRA recommends; humans decide.

**POC success criteria (define exact numbers with your supervisors before starting)**
- **Catch rate (recall):** AuRA flags ≥ X% of the issues that auditors independently find on a labelled sample.
- **Precision / false-alarm rate:** no more than Y% of flagged jobs are dismissed by supervisors as not worth attention.
- **Explainability:** for flagged jobs, supervisors agree the stated reason is understandable and actionable.
- **Throughput & cost:** the per-job processing cost and latency are acceptable when projected to 13M jobs/year.
- **Adoption signal:** pilot supervisors say the flag list saves time versus their current process.

