## 3. The approach (detailed)

### 3.1 The core idea
For each job, AuRA answers one question in several parts: *is this job normal for this kind of repair on this kind of vehicle?* "Normal" is defined by the distribution of comparable historical jobs plus a set of business rules. Anything that falls outside normal becomes a finding, and the findings roll up into a quality score.

### 3.2 A hybrid design — not "agents do everything"
The most important design decision is to **split numeric anomaly detection from language reasoning**:

- **Numeric checks → statistics / ML.** "Is £/hours/parts-count reasonable?" is a distribution question. Comparing a job against the cost-and-labour distribution of similar past jobs (and flagging outliers) is cheaper, more consistent, and more defensible with a statistical or ML model than with a language model trying to eyeball numbers.
- **Language and judgement → AI agents.** Reading the messy free-text description, reconciling it with the parts/labour, spotting fraud-style narratives, and writing a clear, human-readable finding is what the agents are genuinely good at.

A robust AuRA is this hybrid. The agents orchestrate the checks and assemble the report; the statistical layer does the heavy numeric lifting.

### 3.3 Role of each technique
- **Ontology (build now, lightweight).** The shared definition of a Job, Repair Order, Vehicle, Part, Labour line, Technician, Repair type — plus the expectations and rules ("an annual service requires these operations", "this repair type on this vehicle normally costs in this range"). Without it, "compare against normal" has no anchor. It does not need to be a heavyweight formal ontology for the pilot; a clear schema plus a rule set is enough.
- **Semantic search (essential for the pilot).** Job records contain free text and shop-specific abbreviations. To establish "what's normal for this repair", AuRA retrieves the cluster of comparable historical jobs and standard operation definitions *by meaning*, not exact keywords. Semantic retrieval is how the right baseline reaches the agent.
- **Agents (essential for the pilot).** A pipeline of specialised agents (one per check) coordinated by a supervisor agent that assembles the structured report and quality score. This matches AuRA's existing design.
- **Knowledge graph (optional for the pilot, essential later).** Pure job-level review is mostly single-record. The graph pays off when the question becomes relational — RO-level job stacking, and fleet-level trends across technicians, locations and time. Model the data so it is graph-ready, but do not let the graph block the pilot.

### 3.4 Decision summary

| Technique | Job-level (pilot) | RO-level (future) | Fleet-level (future) |
|---|---|---|---|
| Ontology | Build now — foundation | Reused | Reused |
| Semantic search | Essential | Helpful | Helpful |
| Agents | Essential | Essential | Essential |
| Statistical / ML baseline | Essential | Helpful | Essential |
| Knowledge graph | Optional | Essential | Essential |

