## 5. Step-by-step POC plan (phased)

**Phase 0 — Problem definition & rules (1–2 weeks).** With supervisors, write down exactly what a *good* vs *problematic* job looks like, and the concrete checks (numeric thresholds, required operations, fraud patterns such as job stacking precursors). Define the success metrics. This is the highest-leverage and most-skipped step.

**Phase 1 — Data access & ontology (2–3 weeks).** Secure a representative data sample (e.g. several thousand jobs from one or two locations, across multiple repair categories). Define the ontology/schema and the rule set. Land and clean the data in S3.

**Phase 2 — Baselines & semantic index (2–3 weeks).** Build the statistical norms per repair-type × vehicle-type in SageMaker. Generate embeddings and stand up the semantic index (Bedrock Knowledge Base or OpenSearch).

**Phase 3 — Agent pipeline (3–4 weeks).** Build the supervisor agent and specialist checkers in Bedrock Agents / Strands, wiring the baseline scorer and semantic retriever as tools. Add Guardrails. Tune prompts against real examples.

**Phase 4 — Orchestration & output (2 weeks).** Wire Step Functions to run jobs end-to-end; build the reviewer feed/UI; store verdicts and audit trail.

**Phase 5 — Evaluation (2–3 weeks).** Run AuRA over a **labelled "golden" sample** that auditors have already reviewed. Measure catch rate, false-alarm rate, and explainability. Iterate on rules, baselines, and prompts.

**Phase 6 — Limited pilot (4+ weeks).** Roll out to a small number of supervisors at selected locations. Collect confirm/override feedback and performance data, then refine before any broader deployment.

**Indicative timeline:** roughly **14–18 weeks** for a credible POC through to a limited pilot, depending heavily on how fast clean data and supervisor time become available.

