## 9. Pros & cons of the approach

**Pros**
- Coverage moves from a small spot-checked fraction to effectively all jobs.
- Consistent, repeatable judgement against shared baselines.
- Explainable findings, not a black-box score — supervisors can act on reasons.
- Hybrid design keeps numeric checks cheap and defensible while using agents only where language reasoning is needed.
- Modular and staged: the same foundation extends to RO-level and fleet-level later.
- Largely managed AWS services reduce infrastructure burden.

**Cons / trade-offs**
- Real value depends on good ground truth and clean data, which are often the hardest parts.
- Agents add cost and latency; at 13M jobs/year this must be engineered carefully (batching, model tiering, caching).
- Free-text quality varies by shop and technician, which stresses the language components.
- Building and maintaining the ontology and baselines is ongoing work, not one-off.
- Over-flagging erodes trust fast; precision matters as much as recall.

---

## 10. Challenges, risks & mitigations

| Challenge | Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| Ground truth | Without labelled data, you can't prove accuracy | Have SMEs label a golden set early (Phase 0–1) |
| Data quality | Messy, inconsistent job records degrade results | Invest in cleaning/normalisation; profile data first |
| False positives | Over-flagging destroys supervisor trust | Tune for precision; let supervisors give feedback; rank by severity |
| LLM hallucination | Agents invent findings | Ground every finding in retrieved evidence; use Guardrails; keep numeric checks in the stats layer |
| Cost at scale | 13M jobs/year of agent calls is expensive | Batch processing, smaller/cheaper models for routine jobs, caching, escalate only ambiguous jobs to larger models |
| Latency / throughput | Pipeline too slow for volume | Asynchronous batch via Step Functions/SQS; parallelism |
| Concept drift | "Normal" changes over time | Periodically retrain baselines; monitor metrics |
| Free-text variability | Abbreviations/shorthand confuse retrieval | Semantic search + a domain glossary; entity normalisation |
| Adoption / trust | Supervisors ignore the tool | Explainable findings, pilot with champions, show time saved |
| Governance & security | Sensitive operational/financial data | IAM least-privilege, KMS encryption, audit trail, Guardrails |
| Fraud edge cases | Sophisticated fraud evades simple rules | Combine rules + outlier detection now; add graph-based pattern detection at RO/fleet stage |

---

## 11. Cost considerations

The dominant variable cost is agent (LLM) inference at volume. Practical levers:
- **Tier the models:** route routine, clearly-normal jobs to a small, cheap model and escalate only ambiguous ones to a larger model.
- **Do numeric checks outside the LLM:** the statistical layer handles most jobs without a language-model call at all.
- **Batch, don't stream:** AuRA is a back-office review, so asynchronous batch processing is far cheaper than real-time.
- **Cache** standard operation definitions and per-repair-type baselines.
- **Filter first:** only send jobs that fail a cheap pre-screen to the full agent pipeline.

Model the per-job cost on the POC sample and multiply out to 13M before committing to an architecture.

---

## 12. Roadmap beyond the POC

1. **Job-level (this POC):** validate individual jobs; agents + semantic search + baselines + lightweight ontology.
2. **RO-level:** introduce the knowledge graph (Amazon Neptune) to reason across all jobs on a Repair Order — job stacking, cost aggregation, cross-job patterns.
3. **Fleet-level:** graph + analytics for trends across units, locations, and technicians over time, feeding fleet managers' operational decisions.

Each stage reuses the ontology and agent layer; the knowledge graph and GraphRAG come online when the questions become relational.

